<div id="review_2255185316" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2255185316" />
    <a title="Tom Quinn" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31467977-tom-quinn"><img alt="Tom Quinn" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1574458226p2/31467977.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2255185316?book_show_action=true">Sep 22, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom Quinn" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom Quinn" href="/user/show/31467977-tom-quinn">Tom Quinn</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2255185316" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer6163090571579797322">Known best for twisty dense prose, Pynchon plays a bit more here with what <i>isn&apos;t</i> said. Were it published under a penname I think <i>Inherent Vice</i> would have been appreciated as a wild take on the noir mystery genre and little more. But as it bears Pynchon&apos;s name it comes with a lot of preconceptions and hype that leave it feeling at times weirdly underinflated. It&apos;s just not particularly heavy material, and hard to find much depth to it. Atmospheric as hell, though - Pynchon can write captivating s</span>
  <span id="freeText6163090571579797322" style="display:none">Known best for twisty dense prose, Pynchon plays a bit more here with what <i>isn't</i> said. Were it published under a penname I think <i>Inherent Vice</i> would have been appreciated as a wild take on the noir mystery genre and little more. But as it bears Pynchon's name it comes with a lot of preconceptions and hype that leave it feeling at times weirdly underinflated. It's just not particularly heavy material, and hard to find much depth to it. Atmospheric as hell, though - Pynchon can write captivating scenes with detail so fine and quirks so quirky they hit plenty hard. They don't seem to go anywhere in particular, is the thing. Oh, there's a tickle of thematic revelation for someone seeking the ol' Pynchonian analysis frenzy, but it didn't seem to stick around for me. Pynchon murmurs about how future trends gobble up traditions past, about how a place can have its own personality and what happens then if that place gets displaced...<br /><br /><i>and here was Doc, on the natch, caught in a low-level bummer he couldn't find a way out of, about how the Psychedlic Sixties, this little parenthesis of light, might close after all, and all be lost, taken back into darkness . . . how a certain hand might reach terribly out of darkness and reclaim the time, easy as taking a joint from a doper and stubbing it out for good.</i> (254)<br /><br />...but it's all a little too hazy, a bit too far past focus, and then I snap back to reading it as just a rollicking gumshoe mystery story.<br /><br />3.5 stars out of 5 - quite good fiction and quite entertaining, though not in the same league (perhaps not even playing the same sport) as the rest of Pynchon's work.</span>
  <a data-text-id="6163090571579797322" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


